snippet.textDisplay:
I live in Phoenix, the brutal sun out here is notorious for fading paint and destroying clear coat, but white paint is nearly immune to this, plus it's believed to keep the car cooler. Does anyone know why you never see peeling clear coat on white cars?
However, as white paint ages it's prone to excessive chipping, revealing the grey primer underneath. It's easier to patch these chips than it is to repair that disgusting looking clear coat when it bubbles up and flakes away, but I've always been curious why white paint ages so differently than colors. Is it purely chemical? Do they use a different clear coat?
snippet.textOriginal:
I live in Phoenix, the brutal sun out here is notorious for fading paint and destroying clear coat, but white paint is nearly immune to this, plus it's believed to keep the car cooler. Does anyone know why you never see peeling clear coat on white cars? 
 However, as white paint ages it's prone to excessive chipping, revealing the grey primer underneath. It's easier to patch these chips than it is to repair that disgusting looking clear coat when it bubbles up and flakes away, but I've always been curious why white paint ages so differently than colors. Is it purely chemical? Do they use a different clear coat?

snippet.textDisplay: I bought my first car last year and one of the requirements of my first car is that it had to be blue. Not baby blue, not royal blue, and not a dark navy grey. If I was going to buy a car, it had to be a vibrant blue that didn't look washed out or too dark or light. I ended up going with the Mazda 3 2014 sedan because of my budget, though I was already interested in the Mazda 3 because of the gas milage, but I would have preferred a hatchback. If I had to pick my favorite blue car, it would be the Mazda 3 2018 hatchback. The color of the 2014 models are a bit light for my taste, but was good enough to be my first car. The 2018 models are a much more vibrant blue that is extremely satisfying to me, unfortunately they were $5000 out of my price range.

snippet.textDisplay: My garage is a rightbrain versus leftbrain juxtaposition of color. I just bought a brand new 2020 Subaru Outback XT Touring in their 'Magnetilite" (anthracite) color, which is fairly boring, but I still have my 2010 KIA Soul Sport in Molten Lava (bright red), with a two tone red and charcoal interior. That car had a freaking red dashboard in it! The KIA Soul and Dodge muscle cars were the most colorful of the last decade. But, we are now in darker times and the Subaru will blend in well with these times of darkness...

snippet.textDisplay: I actually miss the darker and more bland colors of the mid 80s to mid 00s, not the brighter ones : dark green, dark red, dark blue, beige and tan. They always gave me a modest, yet classy vibe to them, even back when they were newer. Now I always call them retro colors. I've seen a lot of VW, Mercedes, BMW and Audi painted like that as a kid back in the 90s and they stuck with me. With the exception of black, silver and white, I actually find today's color options brighter.
